sec.p:
In our previous work,9 it has been found that the impurities MgOH+ and H+ in the molten chloride salt, which are produced due to hydrolysis of the hydrated salts (e.g., hydrated MgCl2) during the heating as shown in Eqs. 1–2, could react with the Si element in the commercial alloy SS 310 (containing ~2% Si) to form some Mg–Si oxides (e.g., MgSiO3) at 700 °C (see Eqs. 3–5). The thermodynamic calculations using the commercial software—FactSage® show that the standard Gibbs free energy of the reactions in Eqs. 3–5 at 700 °C is −132, −193, and −212 kJ/mol, respectively, whereas the reaction of HCl with SiC and C (Eqs. 6–7) has the standard Gibbs free energy of +3.2 and +27.6 kJ/mol, respectively. This means that only free Si can react with the corrosive impurities in the molten salt at 700 °C.1MgCl2⋅H2O→MgOHCl+HCl,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
